            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this auto loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses the standard amortizing loan formula to estimate
                your monthly payment and total cost of financing a car. It lets
                you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Enter vehicle price, down payment, trade-in value, sales tax,
                  fees, rate, and term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  See your <strong>amount financed</strong>,
                  <strong>monthly payment</strong>,
                  <strong>total interest</strong>, and
                  <strong>payoff date</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  View a full <strong>amortization schedule</strong> with
                  principal and interest for each payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Switch to the <strong>affordability</strong> tab to find the
                  maximum car price that fits a target monthly payment.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Auto loan payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                Most car loans are fixed-rate, fully amortizing loans. The
                monthly payment \(M\) is calculated from:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ M = P \times \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(P\) = amount financed (loan principal)</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = monthly interest rate (APR ÷ 12)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(n\) = total number of monthly payments (term in months)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>The calculator first determines the amount financed:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Taxable amount} = \max(0,\ \text{Price} -
                  \text{Trade-in}) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Sales tax} = \text{Taxable amount} \times \text{Tax
                  rate} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ P = \text{Price} - \text{Down payment} - \text{Trade-in} +
                  \text{Fees} + \begin{cases} \text{Sales tax}, & \text{if
                  rolled into loan} \\ 0, & \text{if paid in cash} \end{cases}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>How much car can you afford?</h3>
              <p>
                On the <strong>“How Much Car Can I Afford?”</strong> tab, the
                calculator works in reverse. Given a target monthly payment
                \(M\), rate \(r\), and term \(n\), it solves for the maximum
                principal \(P\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ P = M \times \frac{(1+r)^n - 1}{r(1+r)^n} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                It then backs out the maximum vehicle price by adding your down
                payment, trade-in, and subtracting estimated tax and fees.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for choosing the right auto loan</h2>
              <h3>1. Focus on the total cost, not just the payment</h3>
              <p>
                Dealers often emphasize “low monthly payments,” but stretching a
                loan from 48 to 72 or 84 months can dramatically increase total
                interest. Use the amortization table and cost breakdown to
                compare scenarios.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Keep the term reasonable</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>36–60 months</strong> is a common sweet spot for new
                  cars.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>72–84 months</strong> lowers the payment but increases
                  total interest and the risk of being
                  <em>upside down</em> (owing more than the car is worth).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Make a solid down payment</h3>
              <p>A larger down payment:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Reduces your monthly payment and total interest.</li>
                <li>
                  Lowers the chance of being upside down if the car depreciates
                  quickly.
                </li>
                <li>Can help you qualify for better rates.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Watch out for add-ons and fees</h3>
              <p>
                Extended warranties, GAP insurance, and dealer add-ons can be
                useful but also expensive. Enter them in the
                <strong>Fees &amp; add-ons</strong> field to see how they affect
                your payment and effective APR.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is a good interest rate for an auto loan?</h3>
              <p>
                Rates vary by credit score, loan term, and vehicle age.
                Borrowers with excellent credit may see rates in the low single
                digits, while subprime borrowers may face double-digit APRs.
                Always compare offers from banks, credit unions, and online
                lenders.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I finance through the dealer or my bank?</h3>
              <p>
                Dealer financing can be convenient and sometimes offers
                promotional rates, but it’s smart to get a pre-approval from a
                bank or credit union first. That gives you a benchmark and
                bargaining power at the dealership.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I pay off my auto loan early?</h3>
              <p>
                Many auto loans allow early payoff without penalty, which can
                save interest. Some contracts, however, include prepayment
                penalties or use precomputed interest. Check your loan agreement
                before making extra payments.
              </p>

              <h3>How does my credit score affect my auto loan?</h3>
              <p>Your credit score influences:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>The interest rate you’re offered.</li>
                <li>Whether you’re approved and for how much.</li>
                <li>Required down payment or co-signer conditions.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Improving your credit score before applying can significantly
                reduce your total borrowing cost.
              </p>
            </section>
